Full Description: The Expansive™ app's unique, ever-expanding canvas lets you create ideas and brainstorm without limits. Expansive has all the tools you need to explore your ideas by drawing, writing and adding images. You can also collaborate in real-time with teammates, clients and co-workers easily to get to the right ideas better and faster. Have you ever been on a call or find yourself working remotely and wish you could just 'show' your teammates or clients what you are trying to describe?  Have you ever worked on an idea on a whiteboard, called in your co-workers, explained it to them, taken a photo, transcribed it to Powerpoint, emailed it to your client, made edits, etc.?  They  have and they are sick of it. That's what inspired us to create Expansive.  Expansive is built for people in that have ideas and need to communicate them. Expansive is ideal for freelancers, business strategists, marketers, product developers, designers, and anyone who finds themselves wishing they could simply draw out an idea when they’re on the phone or away from a whiteboard. Why use Expansive? If you’re like us, you’ve never really felt that typing away in Word or building a PPT deck ever does the trick.  Scraps of paper, whiteboards bolted to a conference room wall, tracked changes in Word and long email threads are not good enough. They can do better. This is just the beginning. They are building the best platform for real-time idea creation and collaboration in a multi-touch world.  They have got a lot ideas and want to hear from you about what features you’d like to see in Expansive. Please email us at feedback@expansive.io.

On January 1st, 2009 preAmped.com was released as a public beta with a few simple goals: 	Make it easy (for users who just want to know whatâ€:tm:s going on) 	Make it comprehensive (what you need to know in a single place) 	Make it deep (get users involved in the local scenes) preAmped.com is a website that caters to the occasional concert fan by exposing simple searching features backed by a vast database of artists, venues, events, locations, and users.  Functionality takes off with a collection of pages revolving around a single event to capture the experience.  Users can check out the artists, post comments, see who is attending, get venue information, post pictures, purchase tickets, and listen to music.  By linking these items to a single event we can create a sense of a 'local community' around concerts. Imagine capturing the concert from the viewpoint of the fans at a single show then tracking that around the country and throughout the years.  preAmped currently has over 350k artists, tracking 250k events from all over the net. A complex system has been designed to merge and clean web data to give the user a simple presentation.  Every venue has an address that has been standardized, geocoded, and validated via external systems.  Users can go directly to their favorite artist or check out their city no matter the size.   The site is also on top of the latest trends and technologies.  Every event, city, and venue page is geo coded, RSS feeds for each city, URLs  are rewritten, and the team continues to explore vCard tagging and KML exports.  preAmped is a new and growing site with an API to be released soon with the sole purpose of removing the overhead of data processing and spawning amazing new tools, widgets, mobile apps, and websites.

Description: How can any of us recover from illness or manage to stay healthy?
Headquarters Regions: East Coast, Southern US
Full Description: How can any of us recover from illness or manage to stay healthy?  What do any of us actually need to know...or do?  The answer is that it's all a piece of work! Why?  Because both medicine and healing are complex.  Because making the right choices, and then sticking to them, is hard, and the rest of life keeps on happening and happening.  Because our own limitations and foibles seem to keep rearing up.  All of this is so and, yet…what matters more to any of us than a long and healthy life with clear cognition, mobility, and low pain? It all comes down to two key principles:  1. Are we, as humans, learning what we need to know?  2. Are we doing what we need to do?  We must discover a clear direction and then actually do what it takes. I Wonder Doctor is about one lesson at a time.  A single piece of information each week, and then just one step to take. One “aha” moment, followed by one “I can do that” decision. It can be done.

The experienced professionals at United Patent Research believe that the first step should be to cultivate an attitude of critical objectiveness when it comes to a project. Many people become deeply emotionally invested in their ideas, and this attachment can cause them to make unwise decisions during the development process. UPRâs technical team can assist a client with this step by offering impartial advice and feedback early in the development of the product. The second important step in United Patent Researchâs guide to successful invention development involves detailed marketing planning. In order to achieve long-term profitability, inventors must carefully think through the ways in which their products will appeal to consumers and consider with which existing products they may have to compete. UPR staffs professionals who can guide clients through this process. The next series of steps apply to qualities of the potential product: United Patent Research recommends that products be patentable, physically simple, cost productive, and made of common materials, and the company also advises that inventors conceive ways in which their products might capitalize on repeat or add-on sales. Description: Yu Family Clinic is an alternative medical provider that offers accupunture as well as more traditional services.
Headquarters Regions: Greater Los Angeles Area, West Coast, Western US
Full Description: Moses Yu learned acupuncture in China from his father, Fu-Kang, a 19th generation acupuncturist. “When I came home from school, my father had me do my acupuncture even before my homework,” Yu has said. More rigorous study followed and eventually, certification. Coming to the United States in the mid 1960s in hopes to perform acupuncture in Los Angeles, Yu was unable to get licensed since acupuncture was largely unheard of at the time. Undeterred, Yu quickly brought healing to the people in his community by setting up a makeshift office in Chinatown where people would patiently wait on the stairs, knowing that Dr. Yu would soon be providing relief for their various ailments. Dr. Yu's office was one of the few to offer fertility acupuncture in Los Angeles. Dr. Yu was instrumental in drafting a bill to make licensing possible in California. After much resistance from the American Medical Association and then-Governor Ronald Reagan, the bill was finally passed in 1976 by Reagan’s successor – and a firm believer in acupuncture – Jerry Brown. Dr. Yu became a licensed acupuncturist in 1976. Dr. Mei Mei Yu interned at the Yu Clinic in Taiwan from 1965 until she moved to Los Angeles with her husband in 1972. She received her license in early 1977. Since opening their Silverlake acupuncture clinic in 1977, Moses and Mei Mei have treated countless happy patients and have welcomed their children, Moses Jr., Wanni and David, into the family practice.

Description: The Wish Upon A Hero - Hero Club Program was created to engage students in philanthropy while making a direct impact in the lives.
Headquarters Regions: Greater Philadelphia Area, East Coast, Northeastern US
Full Description: Wish Upon A Hero was first conceived by founder Dave Girgenti days after the September 11th attacks on New York City. Dave watched in shocked as thousands of people posted pictures of missing loved ones throughout the city. He realized that there needed to be a faster, more efficient way to connect people in need with those looking to help. That was the moment in which the idea for Wish Upon A Hero was born. Less than five years later, Hurricane Katrina created a similar catastrophic event in New Orleans where hundreds of thousands of people needed immediate help. This time it wasn't just about locating loved ones. Hurricane victims needed everything from healthcare services, food, fresh water, clothing and shelter. As Dave watched thousands of everyday heroes coming to the aide of hurricane victims, it became clear that a community-based helping program needed to be created to help organized the efforts of people wanting to help. The Wish Upon A Hero - Hero Club Program was created to engage students in philanthropy while making a direct impact in the lives of people in their local community. Students have the time and passion to help, they also have the support of their family, friends and local businesses. By empowering the younger generation with the tools to help, we are able to create a network of helping communities across the country. The mission of Wish Upon A Hero is to set up Hero Clubs at every school to empower the students to raise money and awareness for causes in their community. Please support your community and sign up as a student, educator or parent.
